When we call `outer()` and assign the returned value to `innerFunc`, we are essentially creating a closure. `innerFunc` is now a function that has access to the scope of `outer`, even though `outer` has already returned.

When we call `innerFunc()` later, it logs the value of `x` to the console, showing that it still has access to the scope of `outer`.

